[[File:大國玉神社 本殿.jpg|thumb|right|245px|Main hall]]
'''Okunitama Shrine''' (おおくにたまじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Sakuragawa|Q990350|WD=Q990350|1=Sakuragawa, Ibaraki}}, {{ill|lt=Ibaraki Prefecture|Q83273|WD=Q83273|1=Ibaraki Prefecture}}, enshrining {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Ōkuninushi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōkuninushi}}. Its nickname is Myōjin-sama<ref name="annai">Ibaraki Prefectural Shrine Association: [http://www.ibaraki-jinjacho.jp/ibaraki/kensei/jinja/12178.html Shrine guide within the prefecture]. Retrieved November 16, 2013.</ref>. Its former name was Kashima Daimyōjin (Kashima Myōjin)<ref>''Shinpen Hitachi no Kuni-shi''.</ref>. It is listed as a {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} ({{ill|lt=Hitachi Province|Q1055353|WD=Q1055353|1=Hitachi Province}}, Makabe District, minor shrine). Its former rank was {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system#various shrines|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Gōsha|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}. It is also written in old characters as '''大國玉神社'''.

=== History ===
The founding date is unknown. Shrine tradition says it was founded in the {{ill|lt=Yōrō|Q1373061|WD=Q1373061|1=Yōrō}} era ({{ill|lt=717|Q23532|WD=Q23532|lt=717|1=717}}–{{ill|lt=724|Q23549|WD=Q23549|1=724}})<ref name="annai"/>. Another tradition places it in the {{ill|lt=Tenchō|Q1373138|WD=Q1373138|1=Tenchō}} era ({{ill|lt=824|Q30353|WD=Q30353|lt=824|1=824}}–{{ill|lt=834|Q30381|WD=Q30381|1=834}}).

It is an ancient shrine recorded in the {{ill|lt=Rikkokushi|Q1151168|WD=Q1151168|1=Rikkokushi}} and the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}.
* {{ill|lt=Shoku Nihon Kōki|Q1041301|WD=Q1041301|1=Shoku Nihon Kōki}}
** Vol. 6: In the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Ninmyō|Q349271|WD=Q349271|1=Emperor Ninmyō}}, 3rd month of {{ill|lt=Jōwa (Japan)|Q1075605|WD=Q1075605|lt=Jōwa|1=Jōwa (Heian period)}} 4 ({{ill|lt=837|Q25093|WD=Q25093|1=837}}), together with Sashino no Kami of Niihari District, it appears as "'''Ōkunitama no Kami of Makabe District'''" with the note "並預官社。以比年特有靈驗也" (it was admitted to the government shrine register due to especially notable divine efficacy in that year).
** Vol. 15: In the same era, year 12 ({{ill|lt=846|Q30454|WD=Q30454|1=846}}), "奉授常陸國无位'''大國玉神'''從五位下" (granted Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade).
* {{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}
** Vol. 5: In the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Seiwa|Q349243|WD=Q349243|1=Emperor Seiwa}}, 9th month of {{ill|lt=Jōgan (Japan)|Q1075635|WD=Q1075635|lt=Jōgan|1=Jōgan}} 3 ({{ill|lt=861|Q23913|WD=Q23913|1=861}}), "授常陸國從五位下'''主玉神'''從五位上" (promoted to Junior Fifth Rank, Upper Grade).
** Among historical records, only the ''Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku'' records the deity name as "Shutama no Kami"; whether this is the same deity as Ōkunitama no Kami is unclear. Since there are three shrines in Ibaraki claiming to correspond to "Shutama no Kami" (Oishi Shrine in Hokota City, and Kamo-Ōkami-Miko-Shutama Shrine in Sakuragawa City), this is treated as a {{ill|lt=ronsha|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}} (disputed corresponding shrine).
* {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}
** In {{ill|lt=Engi|Q1374325|WD=Q1374325|1=Engi (era)}} 5 (927), listed as one minor shrine in Makabe District, Hitachi Province: "'''Ōkunitama Shrine'''" (one of {{ill|lt=Hitachi Province|Q1055353|WD=Q1055353|1=Hitachi Province}}'s 28 shrines).

In the 11th month of {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}} 12 ({{ill|lt=1699|Q7710|WD=Q7710|1=1699}}), {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Mitsukuni|Q1194944|WD=Q1194944|1=Tokugawa Mitsukuni}} dedicated banners of the four gods and halberd-banners of the sun and moon<ref name="annai"/>.

In the 4th month of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}}), it was ranked as a gōsha.

In October {{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|WD=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 4 ({{ill|lt=1992|Q2060|WD=Q2060|1=1992}}), shrine buildings were renovated.

Old regional gazetteers introduce a scenic site called the "Seven Wells of Okunitama": Miyamae no I, Kugutsu I, Kōshinmae I, Kisaki no I, Fukusen Koshiki I, Fukusen Kome I, and Fukusen Sake I.
